"So, with the factory sights removed (you implied you threw them out) and if I don't buy your scope and rings set up, the rifle will have NO sights then?"

Correct - no sights.  As mentioned, there WERE no sight on it anyway from the factory, AS A PRACTICAL MATTER.  They were useless as teats on a boar hog because they were un-usable.    They could not be used - factory defect - way too low.  So without the scope, the rifle has as many usable sights as it would have had from the factory - which is none.

I still have the sights and two rails I took off and can send them with the rifle - if you want them, I will certainly ship them.  I just don't want anyone thinking you can use the sights...So that no one is dissatisfied in any way with the lack of sights, even if I send these.

title: For Sale:  IMI Galil Model 329 in 7.62 NATO in superb condition
postcontent:
Israeli Military Industries Model 329 Galil in 7.62 NATO (.308 Winchester) caliber, in 99+% condition, with five 25 round IMI magazines (new ones are now more than $150 each). The rifle has seen almost no use, and the same can be said of the magazines (which vary from very little use to no use at all, and never filled with more than 20 rnds despite their holding 25). The three tritium night sights are still glowing just fine and in fact have reached an ideal level of brightness, IMHO (they were all too bright when the rifle was new). The rifle (and mags) were never stored loaded, even with 1 rnd. The gas tube shows no trace of pitting or any other evidence of heating (or of even having been fired aside from the gas piston's centering bosses having gone back and forth over the interior of the tube (I have a picture to prove it). The factory recoil pad (which isn't needed, again in my view) still looks as new. Apparently IMI uses some very high quality rubber or other material as there isn't any of the dryness or cracking usually associated with old recoil pads. As you may know about Galils, the chamber, bore, gas block and operating rod are all factory hard-chromed, the latter being something you won't find on even Valmet Kalashnikovs. Please keep in mind this is probably the world's most reliable and durable semi-automatic battle rifle. I've always felt if I had to shoot steel-cased ammo this weapon would eat the stuff for breakfast, lunch & dinner (and more) without breaking a sweat (or a part) as it's built like an Israeli MBT. Also, besides the forged steel receiver and all steel folding stock (not the aluminum version from which it was copied), the rate of barrel rifling twist never goes out of style, which can not be said of the 5.56mm versions. Also, the .30 cal version of this rifle is far rarer than the 5.56mm model, and interestingly enough, because Galils use the same outside diameter of barrel regardless of caliber, this higher-powered version has a far better balance and is faster to bring into action than the smaller caliber rifle. I know this as fact as I own both types.

I'll pay for shipping to your friendly neighborhood FFL dealer from my friendly neighborhood FFL dealer (I actually haven't any choice as I'm a subject...uh, I mean "citizen" of the Peoples Republik of Oppressifornia), so it has to go to an FFL holder. Only a bank cashier's check or US Postal Money Order is acceptable. Sorry but I can't afford to deposit a bad check and the number of folks unhappy with that online money transfer service (which shall go unnamed here) seems to have developed into legions.

Any questions please ask.

title: For Sale/Trade:  Springfield M1 Garand (1943) with Ammo and Bayonet
location: South of Metro - Faribault - Update, Minneapolis / St. Paul, Minnesota
postcontent:
Update:  There is a sale pending on this rifle.  If the sale falls through I'll update the post.  

This is a Springfield Armory M1 Garand in 30-06 with 6” bayonet, sling, two en bloc clips, 340-rounds of brass factory ammo (PMC 150 grain full metal jacket  / target), and 20-rounds of tracer, in two ammo cans.  

The serial number 1,737,XXX places it as being made in July 1943; certainly in time for military service in WW II.  The stock does not appear to have been restored in any way – that gives you the option of making it a regular range rifle or doing some work to make it a conversation piece that hangs on a wall.  I’ve had it at the range and it went “Bang” the appropriate number of times followed by “Ching” when the rounds were gone and the clip extracted…  That’s very high on the cool factor if you’re a fan of WW II firearms or just history.  

Trades I’m interested in include:  

AR-15 / M-4 with 16” barrel in 5.56mm
AR-10 in .308 with at least an 18” barrel
1911 in .45ACP 
High Standard – Double Nine (.22 LR)

If you are sending me a trade offer let me know the value you place on your trade.  If it’s a high estimate or I’m not familiar with aspects of the firearm (accessories, private manufacturers, etc.) I may ask for a price breakdown, that’s not to insult you it’s to better inform me.  If your trade is worth more we’ll work that out too.

Additional photos available if required.  

I check email at least daily for messages and can reply by text if you include a cell phone number.  

I will need to see a valid state or military ID and fill out two sets of private party transfer paperwork – one for each of us.  

Serial number validation site:  http://usriflecal30m1.com/ProductionGraph.aspx

Update:  A gentleman walked me through some of the markings (cartouches) and it appears this is a Garand that was built for (and likely used in) WW II service and then sent back to the Springfield Arsenal in 1951 to be reworked and used for the Korean Conflict.  Can you imagine the history / service behind this rifle?  


Happy Trails.
